Note: ===================================================================
Note: HIR TO SOLIDITY CODE GENERATOR
Note: ===================================================================
Note: Generates Solidity smart contract code from High-level Intermediate Representation (HIR).
Note: Supports Solidity 0.8+ syntax including contracts, interfaces, libraries, events, modifiers.

Note: Part of the Translation Translation System
Note: Location: compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/backends/solidity/hir_to_solidity.runa
Note: ===================================================================

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as ListCore
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/hir_nodes.runa" as HIR

Note: ===================================================================
Note: GENERATION CONTEXT
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Per-translation context for Solidity emission. output accumulates the
generated source; indent_level controls per-line spacing;
current_contract is a back-pointer to the enclosing HIR class node so
state-variable and function generation can consult contract-level
metadata (e.g. base list, abstract flag) without re-locating the
contract.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Runa struct of three fields: output (String, running source), indent_level
(Integer), current_contract (Integer handle to enclosing contract HIR node
or 0 at file scope). Constructed via create_generation_context with
empty/zero values; current_contract is set/cleared on entry/exit of
generate_contract.
@End Implementation
Type called "GenerationContext":
    output as Integer
    indent_level as Integer
    current_contract as Integer
End Type

Note: ===================================================================
Note: MAIN GENERATION ENTRY POINT
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Top-level driver. Creates a fresh GenerationContext and dispatches to
generate_module which emits the SPDX comment, pragma, imports, types,
and contracts in that order. Returns the accumulated output string.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls create_generation_context, then generate_module(ctx, hir_module),
then returns ctx.output.
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_solidity_from_hir" takes hir_module as Integer returns Integer:
    Let ctx be proc create_generation_context

    proc generate_module with ctx, hir_module

    Return ctx.output
End Process

@Reasoning:
Factory for GenerationContext. Initialises output to empty string,
indent_level to 0, and current_contract to 0 (file-scope marker).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Constructs a GenerationContext value with output="", indent_level=0,
current_contract=0. Returns the new value.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_generation_context" returns Integer:
    Let ctx be a value of type GenerationContext with
        output as "",
        indent_level as 0,
        current_contract as 0

    Return ctx
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: MODULE GENERATION
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Emits the full module preamble (SPDX license, pragma directive) and
then walks the top-level lists - imports, types (structs/enums/errors),
and contracts (contract/interface/library). Solidity files must lead
with an SPDX comment and pragma; this driver enforces that
unconditionally. If the HIR module supplies pragma metadata it is
used verbatim, otherwise a default 'pragma solidity ^0.8.0;' is
emitted.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits the SPDX comment. Reads solidity_pragma_type and _pragma_value
metadata; if pragma_type is non-empty emits 'pragma TYPE VALUE;'
otherwise the default. Iterates hir_module_get_imports, then
_get_types, then _get_classes (which holds contracts/interfaces/
libraries). Each call delegates to the corresponding generate_*.
Blank lines separate non-empty sections.
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_module" takes ctx as Integer, hir_module as Integer:
    Note: Generate SPDX license identifier
    proc emit with ctx, "// SPDX-License-Identifier: MIT\n"

    Note: Generate pragma directive
    Let pragma_type be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with hir_module, "solidity_pragma_type"
    Let pragma_value be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with hir_module, "solidity_pragma_value"

    Let pragma_type_len be proc string_length from StringCore with pragma_type
    If pragma_type_len is greater than 0:
        proc emit with ctx, "pragma "
        proc emit with ctx, pragma_type
        proc emit with ctx, " "
        proc emit with ctx, pragma_value
        proc emit with ctx, ";\n\n"
    Otherwise:
        Note: Default pragma
        proc emit with ctx, "pragma solidity ^0.8.0;\n\n"
    End If

    Note: Generate imports
    Let imports be proc hir_module_get_imports from HIR with hir_module
    Let import_count be proc list_length from ListCore with imports
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than import_count:
        Let import_node be proc list_get from ListCore with imports, i
        proc generate_import with ctx, import_node
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    If import_count is greater than 0:
        proc emit with ctx, "\n"
    End If

    Note: Generate types (structs, enums, errors)
    Let types be proc hir_module_get_types from HIR with hir_module
    Let type_count be proc list_length from ListCore with types
    Set i to 0

    While i is less than type_count:
        Let type_node be proc list_get from ListCore with types, i
        proc generate_type with ctx, type_node
        proc emit with ctx, "\n"
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Generate contracts, interfaces, and libraries
    Let classes be proc hir_module_get_classes from HIR with hir_module
    Let class_count be proc list_length from ListCore with classes
    Set i to 0

    While i is less than class_count:
        Let class_node be proc list_get from ListCore with classes, i
        proc generate_contract with ctx, class_node
        proc emit with ctx, "\n"
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: IMPORT GENERATION
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Emits 'import "path";' or 'import "path" as Alias;'. Solidity's import
target is always quoted (a path or URI) unlike most languages'
identifier-based imports; the alias clause is optional and recorded
in metadata.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads import name. Emits 'import "', name, '"'. Reads
'solidity_alias' metadata; if non-empty emits ' as ALIAS'. Terminates
with ';\n'.
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_import" takes ctx as Integer, import_node as Integer:
    Let import_name be proc hir_import_get_name from HIR with import_node

    proc emit with ctx, "import "
    proc emit with ctx, "\""
    proc emit with ctx, import_name
    proc emit with ctx, "\""

    Note: Check for alias
    Let alias be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with import_node, "solidity_alias"
    Let alias_len be proc string_length from StringCore with alias
    If alias_len is greater than 0:
        proc emit with ctx, " as "
        proc emit with ctx, alias
    End If

    proc emit with ctx, ";\n"
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: TYPE GENERATION (STRUCTS, ENUMS, ERRORS)
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Top-level type-declaration dispatcher. Solidity's type-level
declarations split into three distinct keywords (struct, enum, error
- each introduced in different language versions). The
'solidity_type' metadata key selects which generator to invoke; an
unrecognised value silently produces no output, which is the right
behaviour for forward-compatible HIR extensions.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads 'solidity_type' metadata. Branches on string_equals match:
"struct" -> generate_struct; "enum" -> generate_enum; "error" ->
generate_error. Other values fall through with no emission.
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_type" takes ctx as Integer, type_node as Integer:
    Let solidity_type be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with type_node, "solidity_type"

    Let is_struct be proc string_equals from StringCore with solidity_type, "struct"
    Let is_enum be proc string_equals from StringCore with solidity_type, "enum"
    Let is_error be proc string_equals from StringCore with solidity_type, "error"

    If is_struct is equal to 1:
        proc generate_struct with ctx, type_node
    Otherwise:
        If is_enum is equal to 1:
            proc generate_enum with ctx, type_node
        Otherwise:
            If is_error is equal to 1:
                proc generate_error with ctx, type_node
            End If
        End If
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emits 'struct Name { type1 field1; type2 field2; ... }' for a
Solidity value-type aggregate. Each field is emitted with its
Solidity type (from 'solidity_field_type' metadata) followed by the
field name.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads struct name. Emits 'struct NAME {\n'. increase_indent. Loops
hir_type_get_fields: each field becomes
'<indent>TYPE NAME;\n'. The TYPE comes from 'solidity_field_type'
metadata via generate_type_expression. decrease_indent. Emits '}\n'.
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_struct" takes ctx as Integer, struct_node as Integer:
    Let struct_name be proc hir_type_get_name from HIR with struct_node

    proc emit with ctx, "struct "
    proc emit with ctx, struct_name
    proc emit with ctx, " {\n"

    proc increase_indent from ctx

    Note: Generate fields
    Let fields be proc hir_type_get_fields from HIR with struct_node
    Let field_count be proc list_length from ListCore with fields
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than field_count:
        Let field be proc list_get from ListCore with fields, i
        Let field_name be proc hir_field_get_name from HIR with field
        Let field_type be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with field, "solidity_field_type"

        proc emit_indent from ctx
        proc generate_type_expression with ctx, field_type
        proc emit with ctx, " "
        proc emit with ctx, field_name
        proc emit with ctx, ";\n"

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc decrease_indent from ctx
    proc emit with ctx, "}\n"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emits 'enum Name { V1, V2, ... }' for a Solidity enum. Variant names
are stored in the enum node's metadata under the 'solidity_enum_value'
key (potentially multiple occurrences); get_all_metadata_values
collects them in declared order.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads enum name. Emits 'enum NAME {\n'. increase_indent. Pulls the
metadata map via hir_type_get_metadata, collects values under
"solidity_enum_value" via get_all_metadata_values. Iterates the
returned list: each variant is emitted on its own indented line with
a trailing comma except the last. decrease_indent + '}\n'.
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_enum" takes ctx as Integer, enum_node as Integer:
    Let enum_name be proc hir_type_get_name from HIR with enum_node

    proc emit with ctx, "enum "
    proc emit with ctx, enum_name
    proc emit with ctx, " {\n"

    proc increase_indent from ctx

    Note: Get enum values from metadata
    Let metadata be proc hir_type_get_metadata from HIR with enum_node
    Let values be proc get_all_metadata_values with metadata, "solidity_enum_value"

    Let value_count be proc list_length from ListCore with values
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than value_count:
        Let value be proc list_get from ListCore with values, i

        proc emit_indent from ctx
        proc emit with ctx, value

        If i is less than value_count minus 1:
            proc emit with ctx, ","
        End If

        proc emit with ctx, "\n"
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc decrease_indent from ctx
    proc emit with ctx, "}\n"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emits a Solidity 0.8.4+ custom error declaration:
'error Name(type1 field1, type2 field2);'. Errors are file-scope
constructs (unlike struct/enum which can also live inside contracts)
and form the typed counterpart to require/revert messages, enabling
gas-efficient diagnostics.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads error name. Emits 'error NAME('. Iterates hir_type_get_fields:
each field becomes 'TYPE NAME' separated by ', '. The TYPE comes
from the field's 'type' metadata via generate_type_expression.
Terminates with ');\n'.
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_error" takes ctx as Integer, error_node as Integer:
    Let error_name be proc hir_type_get_name from HIR with error_node

    proc emit with ctx, "error "
    proc emit with ctx, error_name
    proc emit with ctx, "("

    Note: Generate error parameters
    Let fields be proc hir_type_get_fields from HIR with error_node
    Let field_count be proc list_length from ListCore with fields
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than field_count:
        Let field be proc list_get from ListCore with fields, i
        Let field_name be proc hir_field_get_name from HIR with field
        Let field_type be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with field, "type"

        proc generate_type_expression with ctx, field_type
        proc emit with ctx, " "
        proc emit with ctx, field_name

        If i is less than field_count minus 1:
            proc emit with ctx, ", "
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc emit with ctx, ");\n"
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: CONTRACT GENERATION
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Emits a Solidity contract, interface, or library declaration with
all members. Solidity distinguishes three top-level container forms:
'contract' (default), 'interface' (no state, no implementations),
and 'library' (no state, no inheritance, stateless utilities). The
'solidity_type' metadata key selects the keyword; the 'solidity_abstract'
metadata flag adds the 'abstract' prefix (Solidity 0.6+). Inheritance
is expressed via 'is Base1, Base2'. The proc saves and restores
ctx.current_contract so member generators (state vars, modifiers,
functions) can consult enclosing-contract metadata.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads contract name and 'solidity_type'/'solidity_abstract' metadata.
Emits 'abstract ' if applicable, then the keyword ('contract' /
'interface' / 'library'), then the name. Reads
'solidity_inherits' metadata via get_all_metadata_values; if non-
empty emits ' is B1, B2, ...'. Emits ' {\n'. Increases indent, sets
ctx.current_contract = contract_node. Calls generate_using_directives
then walks fields (-> generate_state_variable) and methods (each
method's 'solidity_type' metadata routes to generate_event /
_modifier / _function). Blank lines separate non-empty groups and
adjacent methods. Decreases indent, clears current_contract, emits
'}\n'.
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_contract" takes ctx as GenerationContext, contract_node as Integer:
    Let contract_name be proc hir_class_get_name from HIR with contract_node

    Note: Check contract type (contract, interface, library)
    Let solidity_type be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with contract_node, "solidity_type"

    Let is_interface be proc string_equals from StringCore with solidity_type, "interface"
    Let is_library be proc string_equals from StringCore with solidity_type, "library"

    Note: Check for abstract modifier
    Let is_abstract be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with contract_node, "solidity_abstract"
    Let abstract_len be proc string_length from StringCore with is_abstract
    If abstract_len is greater than 0:
        proc emit with ctx, "abstract "
    End If

    Note: Emit contract keyword
    If is_interface is equal to 1:
        proc emit with ctx, "interface "
    Otherwise:
        If is_library is equal to 1:
            proc emit with ctx, "library "
        Otherwise:
            proc emit with ctx, "contract "
        End If
    End If

    proc emit with ctx, contract_name

    Note: Emit inheritance
    Let inherits_meta be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with contract_node, "solidity_inherits"
    Let bases be proc get_all_metadata_values with inherits_meta
    Let base_count be proc list_length from ListCore with bases
    If base_count is greater than 0:
        proc emit with ctx, " is "

        Let i be 0
        While i is less than base_count:
            Let base_name be proc list_get from ListCore with bases, i
            proc emit with ctx, base_name

            If i is less than base_count minus 1:
                proc emit with ctx, ", "
            End If

            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    proc emit with ctx, " {\n"

    proc increase_indent from ctx
    Set ctx.current_contract to contract_node

    Note: Generate using directives (if any in contract scope)
    proc generate_using_directives with ctx, contract_node

    Note: Generate state variables
    Let fields be proc hir_class_get_fields from HIR with contract_node
    Let field_count be proc list_length from ListCore with fields
    Set i to 0

    While i is less than field_count:
        Let field be proc list_get from ListCore with fields, i
        proc generate_state_variable with ctx, field
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    If field_count is greater than 0:
        proc emit with ctx, "\n"
    End If

    Note: Generate events, modifiers, and functions
    Let methods be proc hir_class_get_methods from HIR with contract_node
    Let method_count be proc list_length from ListCore with methods
    Set i to 0

    While i is less than method_count:
        Let method be proc list_get from ListCore with methods, i
        Let method_solidity_type be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with method, "solidity_type"

        Let is_event be proc string_equals from StringCore with method_solidity_type, "event"
        Let is_modifier be proc string_equals from StringCore with method_solidity_type, "modifier"

        If is_event is equal to 1:
            proc generate_event with ctx, method
        Otherwise:
            If is_modifier is equal to 1:
                proc generate_modifier with ctx, method
            Otherwise:
                proc generate_function with ctx, method
            End If
        End If

        If i is less than method_count minus 1:
            proc emit with ctx, "\n"
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc decrease_indent from ctx
    Set ctx.current_contract to 0

    proc emit with ctx, "}\n"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emits 'using LIB for TYPE;' directives inside a contract. The
directive attaches a library's free functions as methods on instances
of the target type (e.g. 'using SafeMath for uint256' makes
'a.add(b)' resolve to 'SafeMath.add(a, b)'). A missing target_type
metadata is interpreted as the global form 'using LIB for *' (file
scope only in Solidity 0.8.13+, but emitted here unconditionally for
backward-compat HIR shapes).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads 'solidity_using' metadata. Returns early if absent. Pulls the
list of directives via get_metadata_list; returns early if empty.
Iterates: each directive carries 'library' and 'for_type' fields.
If library is non-null: emit_indent, 'using LIB for '; emit either
target_type or '*'; ';\n'. Returns 1 to signal completion.
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_using_directives" takes ctx as Integer, contract_node as Integer:
    Note: Generate Solidity using directives (e.g., using SafeMath for uint256)
    Note: Using directives attach library functions to types

    Note: Get using directives from contract metadata
    Let metadata be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with contract_node, "solidity_using"

    If metadata is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Metadata should be a list of using directive objects
    Let using_list be proc get_metadata_list from HIR with metadata

    If using_list is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let using_count be proc list_length from ListCore with using_list
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than using_count:
        Let using_directive be proc list_get from ListCore with using_list, i

        Note: Each directive has: library_name and target_type
        Let library_name be proc get_field from HIR with using_directive, "library"
        Let target_type be proc get_field from HIR with using_directive, "for_type"

        If library_name is not equal to 0:
            proc emit_indent from ctx
            proc emit with ctx, "using "
            proc emit with ctx, library_name
            proc emit with ctx, " for "

            If target_type is not equal to 0:
                proc emit with ctx, target_type
            Otherwise:
                Note: Global using (for all types)
                proc emit with ctx, "*"
            End If

            proc emit with ctx, ";\n"
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: STATE VARIABLE GENERATION
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Emits a contract state-variable declaration:
'TYPE [modifier...] NAME [= INIT];'. Solidity modifiers for state
variables include visibility (public/internal/private) and storage
classifiers (constant/immutable). They can appear in either order
between the type and the name. The modifier list is collected from
'solidity_modifier' metadata which may have multiple values.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
emit_indent. Reads modifier list via get_all_metadata_values keyed by
'solidity_modifier'. Emits 'TYPE ' from 'solidity_type' metadata via
generate_type_expression. Then emits each modifier followed by a
space. Emits the field_name. If 'solidity_initializer' metadata is
non-null emits ' = INIT' via generate_expression. Terminates with
';\n'.
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_state_variable" takes ctx as Integer, field_node as Integer:
    Let field_name be proc hir_field_get_name from HIR with field_node

    proc emit_indent from ctx

    Note: Get visibility and modifiers
    Let modifiers_meta_field be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with field_node, "solidity_modifier"
    Let modifiers be proc get_all_metadata_values with modifiers_meta_field
    Let modifier_count be proc list_length from ListCore with modifiers

    Note: Emit type
    Let field_type be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with field_node, "solidity_type"
    proc generate_type_expression with ctx, field_type
    proc emit with ctx, " "

    Note: Emit modifiers (public, private, internal, constant, immutable)
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than modifier_count:
        Let modifier be proc list_get from ListCore with modifiers, i
        proc emit with ctx, modifier
        proc emit with ctx, " "
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc emit with ctx, field_name

    Note: Emit initializer if present
    Let initializer be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with field_node, "solidity_initializer"
    If initializer is not equal to 0:
        proc emit with ctx, " = "
        proc generate_expression with ctx, initializer
    End If

    proc emit with ctx, ";\n"
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: EVENT GENERATION
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Emits 'event Name(type1 indexed? name1, ...);'. Each event parameter
may carry the 'indexed' modifier (up to 3 per event in Solidity)
which causes the parameter to be stored in a log topic for efficient
indexed access. The 'anonymous' event-level modifier removes the
event's identifier topic - emitted via the 'solidity_anonymous'
metadata flag.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
emit_indent + 'event NAME('. Loops parameters; each yields
'TYPE [indexed] [NAME]'. The 'indexed' keyword is emitted when
'solidity_indexed' metadata is non-empty. Parameters separated by
', '. After ')', emits ' anonymous' when 'solidity_anonymous'
metadata is non-empty. Terminates with ';\n'.
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_event" takes ctx as Integer, event_node as Integer:
    Let event_name be proc hir_function_get_name from HIR with event_node

    proc emit_indent from ctx
    proc emit with ctx, "event "
    proc emit with ctx, event_name
    proc emit with ctx, "("

    Note: Generate event parameters
    Let params be proc hir_function_get_parameters from HIR with event_node
    Let param_count be proc list_length from ListCore with params
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than param_count:
        Let param be proc list_get from ListCore with params, i
        Let param_name be proc hir_parameter_get_name from HIR with param
        Let param_type be proc hir_parameter_get_type from HIR with param

        proc generate_type_expression with ctx, param_type

        Note: Check for indexed modifier
        Let is_indexed be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with param, "solidity_indexed"
        Let indexed_len be proc string_length from StringCore with is_indexed
        If indexed_len is greater than 0:
            proc emit with ctx, " indexed"
        End If

        Let param_name_len be proc string_length from StringCore with param_name
        If param_name_len is greater than 0:
            proc emit with ctx, " "
            proc emit with ctx, param_name
        End If

        If i is less than param_count minus 1:
            proc emit with ctx, ", "
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc emit with ctx, ")"

    Note: Check for anonymous modifier
    Let is_anonymous be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with event_node, "solidity_anonymous"
    Let anon_len be proc string_length from StringCore with is_anonymous
    If anon_len is greater than 0:
        proc emit with ctx, " anonymous"
    End If

    proc emit with ctx, ";\n"
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: MODIFIER GENERATION
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Emits a Solidity modifier definition:
'modifier NAME(params) [virtual/override] { body... }'. Modifiers are
re-usable pre/post-condition fragments composed onto functions. The
'_;' placeholder represents the wrapped function's body and must be
present somewhere in the modifier; when no body is provided this
generator emits a minimal '{ _; }' so the output is syntactically
valid.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
emit_indent + 'modifier NAME(' + comma-separated 'TYPE NAME'
parameters + ')'. Calls generate_function_modifiers to append
virtual/override and other tag modifiers. Emits ' '. If body is
non-null, delegates to generate_statement. Otherwise emits a default
empty body '{\n    _;\n}\n'.
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_modifier" takes ctx as Integer, modifier_node as Integer:
    Let modifier_name be proc hir_function_get_name from HIR with modifier_node

    proc emit_indent from ctx
    proc emit with ctx, "modifier "
    proc emit with ctx, modifier_name

    Note: Generate parameters
    proc emit with ctx, "("

    Let params be proc hir_function_get_parameters from HIR with modifier_node
    Let param_count be proc list_length from ListCore with params
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than param_count:
        Let param be proc list_get from ListCore with params, i
        Let param_name be proc hir_parameter_get_name from HIR with param
        Let param_type be proc hir_parameter_get_type from HIR with param

        proc generate_type_expression with ctx, param_type
        proc emit with ctx, " "
        proc emit with ctx, param_name

        If i is less than param_count minus 1:
            proc emit with ctx, ", "
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc emit with ctx, ")"

    Note: Generate virtual/override if present
    proc generate_function_modifiers with ctx, modifier_node

    proc emit with ctx, " "

    Note: Generate body
    Let body be proc hir_function_get_body from HIR with modifier_node
    If body is not equal to 0:
        proc generate_statement with ctx, body
    Otherwise:
        proc emit with ctx, "{\n"
        proc emit_indent from ctx
        proc emit with ctx, "    _;\n"
        proc emit_indent from ctx
        proc emit with ctx, "}\n"
    End If
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: FUNCTION GENERATION
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Emits a Solidity function declaration. Covers the four function
forms: regular 'function NAME', the unnamed 'constructor', the
unnamed 'fallback', and the unnamed 'receive'. Parameters carry an
optional storage location (memory/calldata/storage) emitted between
type and name. Returns clause uses the 'solidity_returns' metadata
which holds a parameter list (each entry can name its return slot).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
emit_indent. Reads 'solidity_type' metadata. Branches:
  "constructor" -> 'constructor'
  "fallback"    -> 'fallback'
  "receive"     -> 'receive'
  else          -> 'function NAME'
Emits '('. Loops params: emits TYPE via generate_type_expression;
emits ' STORAGE' if 'solidity_storage' metadata is non-empty; emits
' NAME' if name is non-empty. Parameters separated by ', '. Emits
')'. Calls generate_function_modifiers (visibility/mutability/etc).
If 'solidity_returns' metadata is non-null emits ' returns (' +
comma-separated parameter list via generate_parameter + ')'. If
body is non-null emits ' ' + generate_statement; otherwise ';\n'.
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_function" takes ctx as Integer, function_node as Integer:
    Let function_name be proc hir_function_get_name from HIR with function_node
    Let solidity_type be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with function_node, "solidity_type"

    proc emit_indent from ctx

    Note: Check for special function types
    Let is_constructor be proc string_equals from StringCore with solidity_type, "constructor"
    Let is_fallback be proc string_equals from StringCore with solidity_type, "fallback"
    Let is_receive be proc string_equals from StringCore with solidity_type, "receive"

    If is_constructor is equal to 1:
        proc emit with ctx, "constructor"
    Otherwise:
        If is_fallback is equal to 1:
            proc emit with ctx, "fallback"
        Otherwise:
            If is_receive is equal to 1:
                proc emit with ctx, "receive"
            Otherwise:
                proc emit with ctx, "function "
                proc emit with ctx, function_name
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Generate parameters
    proc emit with ctx, "("

    Let params be proc hir_function_get_parameters from HIR with function_node
    Let param_count be proc list_length from ListCore with params
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than param_count:
        Let param be proc list_get from ListCore with params, i
        Let param_name be proc hir_parameter_get_name from HIR with param
        Let param_type be proc hir_parameter_get_type from HIR with param

        proc generate_type_expression with ctx, param_type

        Note: Check for storage location
        Let storage_loc be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with param, "solidity_storage"
        Let storage_len be proc string_length from StringCore with storage_loc
        If storage_len is greater than 0:
            proc emit with ctx, " "
            proc emit with ctx, storage_loc
        End If

        Let param_name_len be proc string_length from StringCore with param_name
        If param_name_len is greater than 0:
            proc emit with ctx, " "
            proc emit with ctx, param_name
        End If

        If i is less than param_count minus 1:
            proc emit with ctx, ", "
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc emit with ctx, ")"

    Note: Generate function modifiers (visibility, mutability, virtual, override)
    proc generate_function_modifiers with ctx, function_node

    Note: Generate returns if present
    Let return_types be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with function_node, "solidity_returns"
    If return_types is not equal to 0:
        proc emit with ctx, " returns ("

        Let return_count be proc list_length from ListCore with return_types
        Let j be 0

        While j is less than return_count:
            Let return_param be proc list_get from ListCore with return_types, j
            proc generate_parameter with ctx, return_param

            If j is less than return_count minus 1:
                proc emit with ctx, ", "
            End If

            Set j to j plus 1
        End While

        proc emit with ctx, ")"
    End If

    Note: Generate body
    Let body be proc hir_function_get_body from HIR with function_node
    If body is not equal to 0:
        proc emit with ctx, " "
        proc generate_statement with ctx, body
    Otherwise:
        proc emit with ctx, ";\n"
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emits the modifier-list tail of a function or modifier declaration:
the space-separated tags visibility (public/private/internal/external),
mutability (view/pure/payable), virtual, override, and any custom
modifiers like 'onlyOwner'. The order follows the HIR-supplied
sequence verbatim because Solidity is lenient about modifier ordering.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Collects modifier list from 'solidity_modifier' metadata via
get_all_metadata_values. Iterates; each entry is emitted as ' TAG'
(leading space). No trailing semicolon or newline - the caller
controls termination.
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_function_modifiers" takes ctx as Integer, function_node as Integer:
    Let modifiers_meta_func be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with function_node, "solidity_modifier"
    Let modifiers be proc get_all_metadata_values with modifiers_meta_func
    Let modifier_count be proc list_length from ListCore with modifiers

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than modifier_count:
        Let modifier be proc list_get from ListCore with modifiers, i
        proc emit with ctx, " "
        proc emit with ctx, modifier
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Single-parameter emitter used for return-list parameters (the
function-argument list inlines parameter emission for tighter
control over the comma-separator logic). Emits 'TYPE [STORAGE] [NAME]'.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads param_name and param_type. Emits TYPE via
generate_type_expression. Reads 'solidity_storage' metadata; if non-
empty appends ' STORAGE'. Emits ' NAME' if name is non-empty (named
returns are an optional Solidity feature).
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_parameter" takes ctx as Integer, param_node as Integer:
    Let param_name be proc hir_parameter_get_name from HIR with param_node
    Let param_type be proc hir_parameter_get_type from HIR with param_node

    proc generate_type_expression with ctx, param_type

    Note: Check for storage location
    Let storage_loc be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with param_node, "solidity_storage"
    Let storage_len be proc string_length from StringCore with storage_loc
    If storage_len is greater than 0:
        proc emit with ctx, " "
        proc emit with ctx, storage_loc
    End If

    Let param_name_len be proc string_length from StringCore with param_name
    If param_name_len is greater than 0:
        proc emit with ctx, " "
        proc emit with ctx, param_name
    End If
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: STATEMENT GENERATION
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Statement-level dispatcher. Unlike PHP's backend which uses a single
type-tag read, the Solidity backend uses per-kind predicate helpers
(hir_is_block / hir_is_if_statement / etc.) - this keeps the
predicate logic centralised in HIR but costs an extra call per
candidate kind. Each predicate match short-circuits via Return.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the node's type via hir_node_get_type (used only for the
default-case fallthrough; predicates do their own type-tag inspection
internally). Cascade: hir_is_block -> generate_block; _is_if -> _if;
_is_while -> _while; _is_return -> _return; _is_break -> 'break;\n';
_is_continue -> 'continue;\n'; _is_expression_statement ->
_expression_statement. Unrecognised statement kinds produce no output.
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_statement" takes ctx as Integer, stmt_node as Integer:
    Let stmt_type be proc hir_node_get_type from HIR with stmt_node

    Note: Block statement
    Let is_block be proc hir_is_block from HIR with stmt_node
    If is_block is equal to 1:
        proc generate_block with ctx, stmt_node
        Return
    End If

    Note: If statement
    Let is_if be proc hir_is_if_statement from HIR with stmt_node
    If is_if is equal to 1:
        proc generate_if_statement with ctx, stmt_node
        Return
    End If

    Note: While statement
    Let is_while be proc hir_is_while_statement from HIR with stmt_node
    If is_while is equal to 1:
        proc generate_while_statement with ctx, stmt_node
        Return
    End If

    Note: Return statement
    Let is_return be proc hir_is_return_statement from HIR with stmt_node
    If is_return is equal to 1:
        proc generate_return_statement with ctx, stmt_node
        Return
    End If

    Note: Break statement
    Let is_break be proc hir_is_break_statement from HIR with stmt_node
    If is_break is equal to 1:
        proc emit_indent from ctx
        proc emit with ctx, "break;\n"
        Return
    End If

    Note: Continue statement
    Let is_continue be proc hir_is_continue_statement from HIR with stmt_node
    If is_continue is equal to 1:
        proc emit_indent from ctx
        proc emit with ctx, "continue;\n"
        Return
    End If

    Note: Expression statement
    Let is_expr_stmt be proc hir_is_expression_statement from HIR with stmt_node
    If is_expr_stmt is equal to 1:
        proc generate_expression_statement with ctx, stmt_node
        Return
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emits a Solidity brace-delimited block. The opening brace lands on
the current cursor position (no fresh emit_indent) so 'if (...) {'
and similar can attach the brace to the previous line.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits '{\n'. increase_indent. Loops hir_block_get_statements,
recursing generate_statement for each. decrease_indent. emit_indent
+ '}\n'.
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_block" takes ctx as Integer, block_node as Integer:
    proc emit with ctx, "{\n"

    proc increase_indent from ctx

    Let statements be proc hir_block_get_statements from HIR with block_node
    Let stmt_count be proc list_length from ListCore with statements
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than stmt_count:
        Let stmt be proc list_get from ListCore with statements, i
        proc generate_statement with ctx, stmt
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc decrease_indent from ctx
    proc emit_indent from ctx
    proc emit with ctx, "}\n"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emits 'if (cond) thenStmt' with optional 'else elseStmt'. Unlike the
PHP backend, this generator passes the branch through
generate_statement without wrapping bare statements in synthesised
braces - the HIR is expected to wrap such cases in a block node
already.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
emit_indent + 'if (' + generate_expression(condition) + ') '. Then
generate_statement(then_branch). If else_branch is non-null:
emit_indent + 'else ' + generate_statement(else_branch).
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_if_statement" takes ctx as Integer, if_node as Integer:
    Let condition be proc hir_if_get_condition from HIR with if_node
    Let then_stmt be proc hir_if_get_then_branch from HIR with if_node
    Let else_stmt be proc hir_if_get_else_branch from HIR with if_node

    proc emit_indent from ctx
    proc emit with ctx, "if ("
    proc generate_expression with ctx, condition
    proc emit with ctx, ") "

    proc generate_statement with ctx, then_stmt

    If else_stmt is not equal to 0:
        proc emit_indent from ctx
        proc emit with ctx, "else "
        proc generate_statement with ctx, else_stmt
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emits 'while (cond) body'. As in generate_if_statement, the body is
passed straight to generate_statement on the assumption that the HIR
already wraps multi-statement bodies in a block.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
emit_indent + 'while (' + generate_expression(condition) + ') ' +
generate_statement(body).
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_while_statement" takes ctx as Integer, while_node as Integer:
    Let condition be proc hir_while_get_condition from HIR with while_node
    Let body be proc hir_while_get_body from HIR with while_node

    proc emit_indent from ctx
    proc emit with ctx, "while ("
    proc generate_expression with ctx, condition
    proc emit with ctx, ") "

    proc generate_statement with ctx, body
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emits 'return [expr];'. The value is optional - bare 'return;' is
the typeless or void-returning form.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
emit_indent + 'return'. If hir_return_get_value is non-null appends
' ' + generate_expression(value). Terminates with ';\n'.
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_return_statement" takes ctx as Integer, return_node as Integer:
    proc emit_indent from ctx
    proc emit with ctx, "return"

    Let value be proc hir_return_get_value from HIR with return_node
    If value is not equal to 0:
        proc emit with ctx, " "
        proc generate_expression with ctx, value
    End If

    proc emit with ctx, ";\n"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emits an expression evaluated for its side effect: 'expr;'. The
emit_indent / trailing ';\n' separation here (rather than inside
generate_expression) keeps expression generation reusable both as a
statement and as a sub-expression of another expression without
emitting stray semicolons.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
emit_indent + generate_expression(hir_expression_statement_get_expression)
+ ';\n'.
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_expression_statement" takes ctx as Integer, expr_stmt as Integer:
    Let expr be proc hir_expression_statement_get_expression from HIR with expr_stmt

    proc emit_indent from ctx
    proc generate_expression with ctx, expr
    proc emit with ctx, ";\n"
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: EXPRESSION GENERATION
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Expression-level dispatcher. Tests each expression kind via the
corresponding hir_is_* predicate and routes to the dedicated
generator. Literal kinds (integer/string/boolean/identifier) are
inlined here because they reduce to a single emit pair.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Cascade of predicate calls: _is_binary -> generate_binary_expression;
_is_unary -> generate_unary_expression; _is_call -> generate_call;
_is_member -> generate_member; _is_index -> generate_index;
_is_integer_literal -> emit raw integer text; _is_string_literal ->
emit '"VALUE"' with quotes; _is_boolean_literal -> emit 'true' or
'false' based on the 0/1 value; _is_identifier -> emit the
identifier name. Unknown kinds fall through with no emission.
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_expression" takes ctx as Integer, expr_node as Integer:
    Note: Binary expression
    Let is_binary be proc hir_is_binary_expression from HIR with expr_node
    If is_binary is equal to 1:
        proc generate_binary_expression with ctx, expr_node
        Return
    End If

    Note: Unary expression
    Let is_unary be proc hir_is_unary_expression from HIR with expr_node
    If is_unary is equal to 1:
        proc generate_unary_expression with ctx, expr_node
        Return
    End If

    Note: Call expression
    Let is_call be proc hir_is_call_expression from HIR with expr_node
    If is_call is equal to 1:
        proc generate_call_expression with ctx, expr_node
        Return
    End If

    Note: Member expression
    Let is_member be proc hir_is_member_expression from HIR with expr_node
    If is_member is equal to 1:
        proc generate_member_expression with ctx, expr_node
        Return
    End If

    Note: Index expression
    Let is_index be proc hir_is_index_expression from HIR with expr_node
    If is_index is equal to 1:
        proc generate_index_expression with ctx, expr_node
        Return
    End If

    Note: Literals
    Let is_integer be proc hir_is_integer_literal from HIR with expr_node
    If is_integer is equal to 1:
        Let value be proc hir_integer_literal_get_value from HIR with expr_node
        proc emit with ctx, value
        Return
    End If

    Let is_string be proc hir_is_string_literal from HIR with expr_node
    If is_string is equal to 1:
        Set value to proc hir_string_literal_get_value from HIR with expr_node
        proc emit with ctx, "\""
        proc emit with ctx, value
        proc emit with ctx, "\""
        Return
    End If

    Let is_boolean be proc hir_is_boolean_literal from HIR with expr_node
    If is_boolean is equal to 1:
        Set value to proc hir_boolean_literal_get_value from HIR with expr_node
        If value is equal to 1:
            proc emit with ctx, "true"
        Otherwise:
            proc emit with ctx, "false"
        End If
        Return
    End If

    Note: Identifier
    Let is_identifier be proc hir_is_identifier from HIR with expr_node
    If is_identifier is equal to 1:
        Let name be proc hir_identifier_get_name from HIR with expr_node
        proc emit with ctx, name
        Return
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emits 'LEFT OP RIGHT'. Unlike the PHP backend, the Solidity backend
does NOT wrap binary expressions in parentheses; the caller is
expected to ensure that the surrounding context respects Solidity
operator precedence, or to insert explicit parenthesisation in HIR
when needed.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads operator, left, right via HIR accessors. Generates left,
emits ' OP ', generates right.
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_binary_expression" takes ctx as Integer, binary_node as Integer:
    Let operator be proc hir_binary_get_operator from HIR with binary_node
    Let left be proc hir_binary_get_left from HIR with binary_node
    Let right be proc hir_binary_get_right from HIR with binary_node

    proc generate_expression with ctx, left
    proc emit with ctx, " "
    proc emit with ctx, operator
    proc emit with ctx, " "
    proc generate_expression with ctx, right
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emits an unconditional prefix unary form 'OP OPERAND' (no postfix
support). Solidity admits prefix '!', '-', '~', '++', '--' on
expressions; the postfix '++' and '--' forms are not generated here -
HIR-side lowering must convert any postfix forms to compound
assignments before reaching this backend.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads operator and operand. Emits operator, then recurses into
generate_expression for the operand.
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_unary_expression" takes ctx as Integer, unary_node as Integer:
    Let operator be proc hir_unary_get_operator from HIR with unary_node
    Let operand be proc hir_unary_get_operand from HIR with unary_node

    proc emit with ctx, operator
    proc generate_expression with ctx, operand
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emits 'CALLEE(arg1, arg2, ...)'. The callee is itself a general
expression so member calls (a.b()), index expressions, and chained
calls all emit correctly through the recursive generate_expression
path.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Generates the callee expression. Emits '('. Iterates
hir_call_get_arguments, generating each and inserting ', ' between
adjacent arguments (not after the last). Emits ')'.
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_call_expression" takes ctx as Integer, call_node as Integer:
    Let callee be proc hir_call_get_callee from HIR with call_node
    Let arguments be proc hir_call_get_arguments from HIR with call_node

    proc generate_expression with ctx, callee
    proc emit with ctx, "("

    Let arg_count be proc list_length from ListCore with arguments
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than arg_count:
        Let arg be proc list_get from ListCore with arguments, i
        proc generate_expression with ctx, arg

        If i is less than arg_count minus 1:
            proc emit with ctx, ", "
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc emit with ctx, ")"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emits 'OBJECT.MEMBER'. Solidity uses '.' for both contract-member
access and struct-field access; the syntactic form is identical so
this one routine covers both.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Generates the object expression. Emits '.'. Emits the member name
verbatim.
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_member_expression" takes ctx as Integer, member_node as Integer:
    Let object be proc hir_member_get_object from HIR with member_node
    Let member_name be proc hir_member_get_name from HIR with member_node

    proc generate_expression with ctx, object
    proc emit with ctx, "."
    proc emit with ctx, member_name
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emits 'OBJECT[INDEX]'. Solidity uses [] subscript for arrays
(fixed-size and dynamic) and mappings. The index expression's type
is determined by the object's type at the HIR layer; this generator
treats them uniformly.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Generates the object expression. Emits '['. Generates the index
expression. Emits ']'.
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_index_expression" takes ctx as Integer, index_node as Integer:
    Let object be proc hir_index_get_object from HIR with index_node
    Let index be proc hir_index_get_index from HIR with index_node

    proc generate_expression with ctx, object
    proc emit with ctx, "["
    proc generate_expression with ctx, index
    proc emit with ctx, "]"
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: TYPE EXPRESSION GENERATION
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Emits a Solidity type reference. The input may be either a raw string
('uint256', 'address payable', 'mapping(...)', etc.) or an HIR type
node. The is_string_value probe lets either form work without the
caller knowing which kind it has on hand - useful because metadata
slots often carry strings while AST slots carry HIR nodes.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls is_string_value on the input. If 1, emits the input directly
(string-literal form). Otherwise treats it as an HIR type node and
emits hir_type_get_name.
@End Implementation
Process called "generate_type_expression" takes ctx as Integer, type_expr as Integer:
    Note: Handle type node or string
    Let is_string be proc is_string_value from type_expr
    If is_string is equal to 1:
        proc emit with ctx, type_expr
        Return
    End If

    Note: Handle HIR type nodes
    Let type_name be proc hir_type_get_name from HIR with type_expr
    proc emit with ctx, type_name
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: METADATA UTILITIES
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
HIR metadata is encoded as an interleaved flat List of
[key1, val1, key2, val2, ...]. This routine collects all values
whose preceding key matches the supplied key string. Some metadata
keys are inherently multi-valued (modifiers, inheritance bases) so
duplicates are preserved in declared order. A null metadata pointer
or missing key yields an empty list rather than null so the caller
can iterate without a null-check.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates a fresh empty List via list_create. Null metadata returns
the empty list. Iterates 0..count in steps of 2: reads
metadata[i] as a key, compares against the requested key via
string_equals; on match reads metadata[i+1] (if in bounds) and
appends to the values list. Returns the populated list.
@End Implementation
Process called "get_all_metadata_values" takes metadata as Integer, key as Integer returns Integer:
    Let values be proc list_create from ListCore

    If metadata is equal to 0:
        Return values
    End If

    Let count be proc list_length from ListCore with metadata
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than count:
        Let metadata_key be proc list_get from ListCore with metadata, i
        Let matches be proc string_equals from StringCore with metadata_key, key

        If matches is equal to 1:
            Let value_index be i plus 1
            If value_index is less than count:
                Let value be proc list_get from ListCore with metadata, value_index
                proc list_append from ListCore with values, value
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 2
    End While

    Return values
End Process

@Reasoning:
Tag-discriminator for the metadata/AST polymorphic input accepted by
generate_type_expression. Tries the HIR-side string predicate first;
if that fails, applies a heuristic memory probe: real
StringCore handles store a length integer in their first 8 bytes
that lies in a plausible range [0, 1MB), whereas AST node handles
store a type tag that does not. The probe is safe on Layout-allocated
memory and avoids false positives in practice for typical Solidity
HIR shapes.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null short-circuits to 0. Calls is_string_hir from HIR; on match
returns 1. Otherwise reads the first i64 at the input pointer and
checks 0 <= length < 1048576; if so returns 1 (likely string).
Otherwise returns 0 (likely HIR node).
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
The memory probe assumes the input pointer is at least 8 bytes of
allocated memory; this is always true for Layout.allocate results
and StringCore handles. Callers must not pass arbitrary integers.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "is_string_value" takes value as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if value is a string by examining its type tag or structure

    If value is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Try to use HIR type checking if available
    Let is_hir_string be proc is_string_hir from HIR with value

    If is_hir_string is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Check if this is a raw string pointer by attempting memory access
    Note: Strings in memory typically have a length field followed by data
    Note: We can check if the first 8 bytes contain a reasonable length value
    Let possible_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with value, 0

    Note: Reasonable string length check (between 0 and 1MB)
    If possible_length is greater than or equal to 0 and possible_length is less than 1048576:
        Note: Likely a string - check if next bytes are readable text
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: If HIR type check returns false and memory check fails, not a string
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: OUTPUT UTILITIES
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
The output primitive: appends a chunk of text to the context's
running output string. Every other generate_* routine flows its
output through here.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
ctx.output := StringCore.string_concat(ctx.output, text). The concat
allocates a fresh string each call; this is O(N) per emission but
acceptable for the bootstrap's small input sizes.
@End Implementation
Process called "emit" takes ctx as Integer, text as Integer:
    Set ctx.output to proc string_concat from StringCore with ctx.output, text
End Process

@Reasoning:
Writes four spaces times the current indent_level. Solidity's
de-facto style guide (per the official documentation) prescribes
four-space indentation; this routine encodes that style.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Loop 0..ctx.indent_level: each iteration emits a four-space string.
No-op at indent_level 0.
@End Implementation
Process called "emit_indent" takes ctx as Integer:
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than ctx.indent_level:
        proc emit with ctx, "    "
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Bumps the context's indent counter so subsequent emit_indent calls
produce one more level of indentation. Paired with decrease_indent
around any nested block.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
ctx.indent_level += 1.
@End Implementation
Process called "increase_indent" takes ctx as Integer:
    Set ctx.indent_level to ctx.indent_level plus 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Companion to increase_indent. The caller must never let indent_level
go negative; the convention is that every increase has a paired
decrease on every exit path.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
ctx.indent_level -= 1.
@End Implementation
Process called "decrease_indent" takes ctx as Integer:
    Set ctx.indent_level to ctx.indent_level minus 1
End Process

